Introduction

You may not realise this but you are surrounded by products and processes that are guided by ISO standards. If youтАЩre a parent, you may own a child seat that has ISOFIX connection compatibility. If you buy some beer or cheese from the store, chances are that the factories making these and the company storing, selling or transporting them will comply with ISO standards for food safety management. There is even an ISO standard for the proper representation of time and date!

Companies can apply for ISO certification to prove that they meet these standards. The certification is done by local member organisations that are usually officially recognised by the government. One such organisation is The British Standards Institution (BSI) which is responsible for the certification process in the UK. In this post, we will explain why looking for ISO certification when choosing your digital medical service, is important.

The importance of ISO standards

ISO themselves describe their standards as a formula that depicts the best way of doing something. A group of international experts in any given field has come together and distilled their expertise into specific instructions on how to do things. If a company is certified to meet certain ISO standards, then it means that a well-respected, often government-recognised, third party has inspected its processes thoroughly and made sure that they follow these instructions.

ISO standards are tremendously valuable for businesses in making sure that they are doing things well. ISO standards also benefit consumers by providing them with assurance that the products and services they purchase are safe, reliable, and of high quality. Nowhere is this more important than in medicine. Of course, medicine is a strictly regulated field anyway and when visiting a doctor, you can be quite sure that they have the necessary training and that their clinic has been reviewed by the appropriate institutions. However, new and innovative online medical services often fall outside of the purview of traditional review boards and regulators. It may take time before legislation catches up to the fast-paced development of technology. Therefore, it is important to be more cautious in choosing your online medical services. ISO certification can serve as a helpful marker of quality.

Types of ISO Standards

ISO standards cover a wide range of industries and topics. If you are interested in seeing them in detail, check out the ISO website for the most common ones. Below, we will review some of the ISO standards that are specifically relevant in digital healthcare.

ISO 9001 series for quality management

While not necessarily medicine-related, ISO 9001 is one of the most commonly used quality management standards and is therefore applicable to medicine as well. This certificate is worth looking for in whatever product or service you're purchasing. The standards are explained in more detail in ISO's quality management principles.

ISO/IEC 27000 for cybersecurity

This is the most well-known standard for information security management systems. Again, this isn't specific to medical services, but given that medical service providers will handle delicate data about you, it is worth making sure that they have the right processes in place to ensure data security. Conformity with ISO/IEC 27001 means that an organization or business has put in place a system to manage risks related to the security of data owned or handled by the company, and that this system respects all the best practices and principles established in this international standard.

ISO 15189 for laboratories

This is a certification for medical laboratories. It details requirements for the medical laboratory to plan and implement actions to address risks and opportunities for improvement. It is aimed at increasing the effectiveness of the management system, decreasing the probability of invalid results, and reducing potential harm to patients, laboratory personnel, the public, and the environment.

ISO 13485 and ISO 14971 for medical devices

These standards are meant to guide companies who are creating, building or servicing medical devices, including digital medical services. Often, regulatory authorities will require the producers to demonstrate their compliance with these standards.

Conclusion

Seeing that a company is certified to meet certain ISO standards can be an important factor in determining whether it is worth trusting your money and delicate information with them. Our catalog allows you to easily compare services in this regard. It is important to note that ISO certification is not the only badge of quality. Check out the catalog to see which ones are out there.

fields.title: How to navigate the Wild West of digital healthcare?
fields.text:
Digital healthcare is rapidly evolving with new technologies and innovations emerging every day. Honestly, it has become a bit of a Wild West out there. For the uninitiated, it may be increasingly difficult to understand which of these services are trustworthy and which are not? Which of them are data-grabbing scams or bad-quality services? Where can you trust your delicate information to stay secure and where to expect leaks? Here are some tips to help you navigate this exciting but increasingly complex terrain.

  1. Check for certifications: Certificates are not necessarily a guarantee that the service you are purchasing will be of good quality or suitable to your needs. However, a business that has put its product through the scrutiny of obtaining a medical device registration (a requirement for many products in this field) can generally be taken more seriously than one that hasnтАЩt. Or a company that proudly boasts its ISO certificates will almost certainly have better internal quality control systems than a company that doesnтАЩt. Therefore, seeing a CE marking or ISO certification on the serviceтАЩs web page is usually a good sign. There are of course different categories for both medical devices and ISO certificates and it doesnтАЩt hurt to familiarise yourself with these. HereтАЩs a blog post where we explain in detail what each of these means.
  2. Look for evidence-based practices: Look for products or services that are using evidence-based practices. This is especially true for any service that offers medical diagnoses, treatment recommendations, etc. This is a tricky one. Evidence-based is one of those buzzwords that get thrown around a lot, to the point where the phrase has become hard to define. Does a recommendation for treatment that is based on a single animal study, published in an online non-peer-reviewed journal qualify as evidence-based? The results of a study are evidence, right? Not quite. All studies are not created equal and determining whether evidence is convincing or not requires a lot of in-depth knowledge about the specific subject, the publication, the scientific methods used, etc. In this case, the recommendation based on the animal study almost certainly doesnтАЩt qualify as enough evidence. Then how should тАЬnormalтАЭ people find their way in this confusing topic? We recommend looking for services that clearly state that their output is based on guidelines. Guidelines (in medicine, often referred to as clinical guidelines) are papers, published by respectable organisations that contain recommendations that a large and diverse group of experts have deemed to be the most appropriate, based on the best available evidence at the time. These may include international clinical guidelines developed by a medical society. For example, if the blood pressure management recommendations you are receiving are based on guidelines published by the European Society of Cardiology, you should feel safe following that advice. Others may be national guidelines, such as NICE guidelines in the UK. These will cover a wide range of topics and are generally aligned with other international (disease or domain-specific) guidelines. In short, if the advice you are given is claimed to be evidence-based, make sure you understand what that actually means and look for mentions of specific guidelines.
  3. Look for third-party reviews. A lot of companies have reviews of their products on their own websites but it is important to note that these may be subject to manipulation by the company. Another technique often used is тАЬuser storiesтАЭ published on the website - these are almost certainly curated for marketing purposes and not intended to give an honest and unbiased opinion of the service. You should, therefore, look for third-party platforms for reviews. While not entirely free of manipulation risk due to the anonymity of reviews, sites such as Reddit, Quora, or Trustpilot might offer some insight into the service. A hint: look for balanced reviews, not ones that are 1 star and тАЬeverything was terribleтАЭ or 5 stars and тАЬgreat service!тАЭ. A review that has 2,3 or 4 stars with a plausible explanation for a deficiency is often more useful. Overall, it is important to note that although these platforms may strive for unbiased reviews, manipulation still occurs. Even other usersтАЩ genuine experience may not always be relevant to yours. Therefore, reviews should only be one aspect of your research.
  4. Protect your privacy: Make sure any digital health product or service you use is secure and protects your privacy. Look for products that encrypt your data and have strong security protocols in place. Generally, it is a good sign if a company has ISO 27000 series certificates that prove that their products conform to certain cybersecurity standards. Many companies will advertise as being compliant with international data protection acts such as GDPR in the EU and UK or HIPAA in the USA. While every business these days has to be compliant with data protection acts, it is important to note that declaring compliance and actually being compliant are two different things. If you want evidence of that, just look for news about large companies being fined for violating the principles of these acts. So how to understand if your data is in good hands? In all honesty, it is very difficult to determine this on your own, without seeing the processes behind the user interface. A couple of things are worth looking out for, though. Look for cookie policy pop-ups. You may have noticed that these annoying little things have become omnipresent in your digital life in the past couple of years. The reason behind that is the data protection laws that require all sites to disclose their policy. If you donтАЩt see any pop-ups for cookie preferences, this should be taken as a red flag. Another thing to look out for is a consent form that informs you about the potential to use your data for statistical and marketing purposes. The GDPR states that any company that wants to use your data for their services has to obtain your explicit consent. Obtaining this consent should include a clear and plain-language explanation as to what type of information and for what purpose they will be gathering. If your consent is not asked or if the consent form is not informative enough, you should think twice about agreeing to the terms.
  5. Endorsements: Look for endorsements by public offices such as the NHS in the UK. Or cooperation with insurance companies. Make no mistake, the absence of such ties is not automatically a bad sign - the overwhelming majority of perfectly good digital health services have no reason to be cooperating with government agencies or insurance companies. However, if such ties do exist, they are usually a sign that someone has done the due diligence on the service or product and has deemed it trustworthy.
  6. Compare products: This is almost too obvious to note, but in the realm of online medical services, this step becomes crucial. The availability and variety of digital health services can be overwhelming, and it might be tempting to choose the first service that seems to meet your needs. However, a more cautious approach is recommended. Begin by evaluating the various options within your desired category. For example, if you are looking for an online consultation, compare the services provided by different platforms, looking at aspects like pricing, features, accessibility, and the qualifications of the professionals available. By doing this, you are broadening your understanding of whatтАЩs out there.
  7. Understand your needs: We left the most important part to the last. It's essential to have a clear understanding of what you need from the service. Are you seeking a one-time consultation, ongoing care, or a specific type of therapy or treatment? Understanding your needs will help you narrow down the options to those most suited to your situation. Coincidentally, not understanding your needs might make it extremely difficult to narrow down your options.

Conclusion

choosing an online medical service doesn't have to be a daunting task. By employing the steps above, you can make an informed and confident decision. Remember, your health and well-being are paramount, and the extra time spent researching and comparing options is a worthwhile investment in ensuring that you receive the best possible care. Here at Hainu, we strive to bring the necessary information together into one place to make navigating the wild west of digital healthcare a little bit easier. Have a look around our website.

fields.title: A Beginner's Guide To Biomarkers
fields.text:
As the market of direct-to-consumer laboratory services continues to grow and new companies are coming in, selecting the right lab tests has become more and more difficult. To get the attention of users, companies are trying to create new and sophisticated packages that contain different lab tests but the logic behind them may be obscure for regular users.

We searched through dozens of laboratoriesтАЩ websites and identified some of the most common biomarkers that you should know about. These can commonly be found in тАЬgeneral healthтАЭ тАЬheart healthтАЭ or тАЬcardiovascular healthтАЭ panels and elsewhere. The list below gives an overview of what these common biomarkers measure and why it may be important to check them regularly. Read through the list and see how you can benefit from testing some of them.

Cholesterol

Measures the total amount of cholesterol in the blood. This test is usually (together with LDL, HDL, and triglycerides) a part of "lipid", "general health" or "heart health" (also sometimes called "cardiovascular health") panels. With high cholesterol, you can develop fatty deposits in your blood vessels. Eventually, these deposits grow, making it difficult for enough blood to flow through your arteries. Sometimes, those deposits can break suddenly and form a clot that causes a heart attack or stroke.

LDL

LDL, or Low-Density Lipoprotein, is a type of cholesterol that is often referred to as the "bad cholesterol." It is the main culprit behind the adverse outcomes of elevated total cholesterol. This test is usually (together with total cholesterol, HDL, and triglycerides) a part of "lipid", "general health" or "heart health" (also sometimes called "cardiovascular health") panels. High levels can lead to plaque buildup in arteries and increased risk of atherosclerosis.

HDL

Often called "good cholesterol." High levels are shown to be protective against cardiovascular disease. This test is usually (together with total cholesterol, LDL, and triglycerides) a part of "lipid", "general health" or "heart health" (also sometimes called "cardiovascular health") panels. Unlike its evil twin brother LDL, HDL levels are difficult to manipulate with medication or lifestyle choices. Its role in cardiovascular health is complex and medication specifically designed to elevate HDL has so far not demonstrated consistent reduction in adverse cardiovascular events such as heart attacks. What this means is that while it is an important risk factor to consider, follow-up testing often has a limited effect on lifestyle and treatment decisions.

Triglycerides

Triglycerides are a type of fat (lipid) found in the blood. They play a vital role in health, but in excess, they can be problematic. This test is usually (together with LDL, HDL, and triglycerides) a part of "lipid", "general health" or "heart health" (also sometimes called "cardiovascular health") panels. High levels can increase the risk of atherosclerosis (narrowing and hardening of the arteries), which in turn raises the risk of heart attack and stroke. Severely elevated triglycerides can lead to pancreatitis, an inflammation of the pancreas.

HbA1c

Indicates the average blood sugar levels over the past 2-3 months. Used to diagnose and monitor diabetes. A normal HbA1c is a a good indication of lack of diabetes whereas slightly elevated HbA1c warrants other investigations such as glucose tolerance testing.

Fasting Glucose

Measures blood sugar after fasting for at least 8 hours. With proper fasting, can be used for diagnosing diabetes. However, a gray area exists and interpretation should be done by a doctor. An elevated measurement is usually followed up retesting or other methods such as HbA1c or the oral glucose tolerance test.

Creatinine (eGFR)

Measures kidney function. High levels of creatinine can indicate kidney damage or impaired function. eGFR or estimated glomerular filtration is usually automatically calculated from creatinine levels and serves as a more reliable marker of kidney damage because it takes into consideration factors that influence normal levels of creatinine.

CBC (complete blood count or hemogram)

Provides information about different cell types in the blood. The exact components of a CBC may vary a bit. WeтАЩve listed the most common ones.

  • Hemoglobin (Hb): Oxygen-carrying protein in red blood cells. Abnormal levels can indicate anemia or other conditions.
  • White Blood Cells (WBC): Measures the total number of white blood cells. Elevated or decreased counts can indicate infection, inflammation, or other conditions.
  • Red Blood Cells (RBC): Measures the number of red blood cells, which carry oxygen.
  • Platelets (PLT): Involved in blood clotting. Abnormal levels can affect bleeding and clotting.
  • Hematocrit (HCT): Percentage of blood volume that is red blood cells.
  • Mean Corpuscular Volume (MCV): Average volume of a red blood cell. Used to classify types of anemia.
  • Mean Corpuscular Hemoglobin (MCH): Average amount of hemoglobin per red blood cell.
  • Mean Corpuscular Hemoglobin Concentration (MCHC): Average concentration of hemoglobin in red blood cells.
  • Red Cell Distribution Width (RDW): Variation in red blood cell size. Elevated RDW can be found in anemias that cause red cell size to change such as iron deficiency, folate deficiency or vitamin B12 deficiency.
  • Mean Platelet Volume (MPV): Average volume of platelets.
  • Neutrophils: Type of white blood cell. Elevation is usually caused by infections. After viral infections, neutrophils may be "reactively" low.
  • Lymphocytes: Type of white blood cell. Can provide insight into immune response and infections.
  • Monocytes: Type of white blood cell. Can provide insight into immune response and infections.
  • Basophils: Type of white blood cell. Can provide insight into allergic reactions or certain infections.

Ferritin

Indicates the amount of iron stored in the body. Low levels can suggest iron-deficiency anemia. May be elevated or falesly appear "normal" in the presence of inflammation.

Bilirubin

A product from the breakdown of red blood cells. Elevated levels can indicate liver (bile duct) dysfunction or hemolytic anemia.

AST

Liver enzyme. Elevated levels can indicate liver injury or disease. Mild elevations are commonly caused by obesity, alcohol abuse or certain drugs while marked elevation may indicate acute hepatitis or drug toxicity. AST is similar to another enzyme, ALT but conditions causing their elevation are slightly different. Of the two, ALT is considered to be the more specific marker for liver disease.

ALT

Liver enzyme. Elevated levels can indicate liver injury or disease. Elevated levels can indicate liver injury or disease. Mild elevations are common in obesity and alcohol abuse and marked elevation may indicate viral hepatitis. ALT is similar to another enzyme, AST but conditions causing their elevation are slightly different. Of the two, ALT is considered to be the more specific marker for liver disease.

GGT (Gamma-Glutamyl Transferase)

GGT is an enzyme that is found in the liver. It plays a role in the transfer of amino acids across the cell membrane, and it also has a role in the metabolism of glutathione, an important antioxidant in the body. GGT is often measured as a part of liver function tests to assess the health and functionality of the liver. Elevated levels of GGT in the blood can be indicative of liver damage or disease. GGT is considered to be a very sensitive marker for liver diseases, especially bile duct problems. Conditions such as hepatitis, cirrhosis, liver tumors, or bile duct blockage can cause elevated GGT levels. Chronic alcohol consumption can also lead to increased GGT levels. It's sometimes used to detect heavy drinking, as the GGT level can become elevated before other indicators show liver dysfunction. GGT is often measured alongside other enzymes like AST (Aspartate Aminotransferase) and ALT (Alanine Aminotransferase) to diagnose and monitor liver conditions. Unlike GGT, ALT and AST are found in various parts of the body, so when liver-specific GGT is elevated alongside ALT and AST, it provides a clearer indication of liver damage.

TSH (Thyroid Stimulating Hormone)

Produced by the pituitary gland. It stimulates the thyroid gland to produce thyroid hormones. Altered levels can indicate thyroid dysfunction. The most common thyroid dysfunction is hypothyroidism, meaning a deficiency of thyroid hormones. This can cause fatigue, constipation, depression, weight gain, anemia and other conditions. Meanwhile, hyperthyroidism, an excess of thyroid hormones, is more rare but also more dangerous than hypothyroidism. Hyperthyroidism can lead to arrhythmias, anxiousness, weight loss, tremor and bulging eyes (GravesтАЩ orbitopathy).

Testosterone

The primary male sex hormone, but it is present in both males and females. Involved in muscle and bone mass, fat distribution, and red blood cell production. Often, free testosterone, the active form is thought to be a better indicator of testosterone deficiency..

Vitamin D3

Measures the concentration of 25-hydroxyvitamin D in the blood, which is the best indicator of vitamin D status. A deficiency can lead to bone loss, osteoporosis, and fractures. Vitamin D3 is also important for immune function and other bodily processes. In healthy individuals who are regularly exposed to sunlight, endogenous Vitamin D production should be enough to avoid deficit. People with kidney disease or otherwise healthy individuals who are not exposed to regular sunlight are at risk for developing Vitamin D deficiency. Vitamin supplementation is often recommended to everyone on the northern hemisphere from September to April.

Vitamin B12

Measures the concentration of vitamin B12 in the blood. B12 is essential for nerve function, red blood cell formation, and DNA synthesis. A deficiency can lead to anemia, fatigue, and neurological problems. Since dietary Vitamin B12 can be found only meat products, people who are on vegan diets should regularly check Vitamin B12 levels. Absorption issues (due to gastritis or alcohol intake) may cause Vitamin B12 deficiency in people with omnivore diets as well.

CRP

Is one of the most common biomarkers used for detecting inflammation in the body. Elevated CRP may be caused by infections, autoimmune conditions and cancers. It is a non-specific marker and cannot distinguish between these causes.

Uric Acid

Uric acid is a waste product produced when the body breaks down substances called purines, which are found in many foods and are also produced naturally by the body. Most uric acid is eliminated through the urine, but if the body produces too much uric acid or doesn't eliminate enough of it, it can build up in the bloodstream. Elevated levels of uric acid in the blood can lead to a type of arthritis called gout. Gout occurs when urate crystals accumulate in the joints, causing inflammation and intense pain. Urate crystals may also form kidney stones. Note that during a gout attack, uric acid levels may actually be lower than usual.

PSA

PSA stands for prostate specific antigen. It is a protein produced by the prostate. PSA is mainly used for prostate cancer screening and treatment tracking. It is important to note that urinary infections, especially prostatitis, and perineal region trauma (including cycling) can also cause PSA levels to rise. Also, prostate cancer malignancy is a complex thing to evaluate and PSA does not distinguish between the very common relatively benign forms from aggressive tumors. Usually, when PSA is elevated, the free form of PSA (as opposed to the protein bound form, which is normally tested for) is measured next to confirm that the elevation is тАЬrealтАЭ.

Summary

This list is by no means exhaustive but if you are in need of a check-up and are not sure which lab tests to pick, the biomarkers described here can serve as a good starting point. Check out the lab companies on our website to see what they might have to offer.

If a medical laboratory has UKAS accreditation, it means that it:
1) Meets recognised standards and regulations
2) Is competent

fields.name: CE
fields.description:
CE is an abbreviation of "conformit├й europ├йenne" (French for "European conformity"). It means that the product bearing this marking conforms to rules and regulations in place in the European Economic Area (EEA), which includes the EU countries, Iceland, Lichtenstein and Norway. 

Although the UK is not part of the EU anymore, it recognises the EU medical device legislation and most products will be allowed on the UK market bearing a CE certificate until June 2028 or June 2030 depending on the category fo the device. It is important to note that this applies to products that already have CE markings. Since the UK authorities cannot issue CE certificates, any medical device registered in the UK (with MHRA), will bear the  UKCA (UK Conformity Assessed) marking. For customers, this is mostly a legislative change since the UK medical device regulation is derived from the EU legislation and the regulatory body remains the same (MHRA). 

What does this mean for customers? CE marking and UKCA marking are both badges of quality and seeing either is a good sign. 

Link to website: https://single-market-economy.ec.europa.eu/single-market/ce-marking_en

The process of repeatedly filling out intake forms, which is particularly challenging for individuals with ADHD, felt disregarded. Results & analysis as accurate as those from regular GP's - with the same accreditation as NHS labs !
Chosen for a reason, accuracy is focus. 

With hundreds of thousands clinical diagnostic tests performed every day, our chosen laboratory strives to excel standards, with each biomarker validated for accuracy & repeatability, whilst contributing to every stage of patient care: predisposition, prevention, diagnostics, treatment monitoring & prognosis.

When your data reaches the lab, itтАЩs encrypted and stored on UK based ISO 27001 accredited servers, following strict guidelines for clinical data transfer. Tracking systems ensure all samples, results & info is monitored and secure, so that only you, the lab and our team of professionals have access.

Accurate, reliable and safe data is vital and HEAL is dedicated in ensuring we provide everything you need to achieve this to better your health!

fields.name: Welzo
fields.description: Welzo is a full-service telemedicine company. Their primary services are At-home lab testing and online pharmacy. You can order finger prick tests to collect blood samples from your home. They deploy an online AI-powered quiz to help you pick out the tests that suit your needs and provide clinical insights. They also offer treatments and online GP consultations for various health issues. Their online pharmacy does home delivery of medications.
fields.bio:
Getting an appointment with your GP can be lengthy and time-consuming. The average patient in the UK has to wait at least 15 days before they can speak to a GP and a further 4 - 8 weeks if a consultation is required. But getting access to quick and affordable healthcare does not have to be this complicated.

That's why we created Welzo. We offer instant online consultations, giving you access to treatment and testing from the comfort of your home within minutes. This is the future of healthcare, no more waiting rooms. We offer personalised testing and medication instantly online and delivered the next day to your house.

fields.name: Ghosh Medical
fields.description: Ghosh Medical has private medical clinics in Liverpool and Manchester. They also sell a limited amount of at-home lab tests. They have an e-pharmacy with the option to order medications online and get clinical consultations.
fields.bio:
Private GP Dr Arun Ghosh offers a private general practice service in Liverpool and Manchester for one-off appointments or ongoing medical care and services for total peace of mind about your health.

You do not have to be a registered patient to use the Private GP service at Ghosh Medical Group. You can book a one-off appointment as often as you like at any of our clinics.

fields.name: Affinity AI
fields.description: Affinity is an AI model that utilizes Generative AI technology to provide individuals with a unique and personalized experience and help with mental problems.
fields.bio:
Our journey began in 2020, when we were pursuing our PhDs and researching chatbots for mental health. We quickly realized that, despite the potential for offering a highly effective treatment option, conventional chatbots were rigid, rule-based systems that were limited to providing generic responses and therefore failed to address the unique needs of each user.

Determined to make digital mental health support more engaging and personalized, we decided to put our expertise and backgrounds in AI and digital mental health to work on creating a more flexible and responsive approach. We spent three years tirelessly researching and developing a solution that would offer personalized and highly responsive dialogues to help people navigate their mental health journeys.

The result is a purpose-built AI model that utilizes Generative AI technology to provide individuals with a unique and personalized experience. Our AI is designed to understand the needs of each user and provide them with tailored support and guidance.

fields.name: Fibricheck
fields.description: Phone camera-based AI tool to help detect Atrial fibrillation. Offer D2C app or prescription from doctor + direct communication between app and doctor.
fields.bio:
FibriCheck is an innovative digital health company dedicated to transforming the way cardiac care is delivered. We do so by providing a medically certified, software-only and device-agnostic solution that redefines the way cardiac arrhythmias are detected and managed.

We empower people to take control of their heart health by offering them our PPG-technology in a user-friendly setting. Users can measure their heart rhythm in 60 seconds, using the camera of their smartphone without any additional hardware. These measurements provide valuable insights into the heart rhythm which help people attain peace of mind and help to improve the outcomes of cardiac arrhythmias by speeding up the process of getting the right diagnosis and treatment.

FibriCheck can be used throughout the entire patient lifecycle, from early detection and secondary prevention to the management of cardiac arrhythmias, such as atrial fibrillation (AF). On top of that, our software can also be used for symptom management such as palpitations, as symptoms can be logged with each measurement. These symptoms are combined with the results of the measurements in reports, which can easily be shared with physicians for further follow-up.

Accuracy and safety are of the highest importance to us, which is why we make continuous efforts towards regulatory compliance and clinical validation. We are a CE class IIa medical device with regulatory approvals of the MHRA, FDA and TGA.

FibriCheck is currently implemented by over 2000 clinical practices, and is the trusted partner in heart health for over 1 million users in 43 countries. Various integration possibilities are available.

fields.name: Peanut
fields.description: Peanut is a social media company that aims to connect women going through similar situations, be it pregnancy, menopause, child-raising, or health-related issues. They also publish womenтАЩs health-related articles and offer ovulation and pregnancy calculators.
fields.bio: We created Peanut with the idea that no one should have to navigate womanhood alone. Especially the hard parts. Our mission is to provide a social network for women to connect across fertility, pregnancy, motherhood and menopause. So far, over 3.5M women use Peanut monthly to build friendships, find support, and learn from one another.

fields.name: IcleTest
fields.description: Icletest is a urine strip test that detects trace blood in urine. It is meant for at-home use and the results can be interpreted at home, without shipping the test anywhere.
fields.bio:
IcleTest is an at home urine test for invisible blood which can be an early warning sign of prostate, kidney or bladder cancer. 

As a practicing GP with over 40 years' experience, he believes testing regularly could be vital to your long term health.

fields.name: Atlas Biomed
fields.description: Atlas offers DNA and microbiome tests. By analyzing the bacterial composition of your gut microbiome, they are able to provide predictions for disease risks and offer nutritional advice on how to improve it. Their DNA testing provides disease risk predictions for 20 multifactorial conditions, as well as 322 hereditary ones. You also receive feedback on your ancestry, sports, and metabolism.
fields.bio: Atlas Biomed is a personalised health company, applying the latest genetic technologies to help you navigate towards your potential. To achieve this, Atlas has two tests available in the UK: the Atlas DNA Test and the Atlas Microbiome Test. Both tests feed into the Atlas platform, which allows you to take control of your health through actionable, personalised recommendations.

fields.name: Selph
fields.description: Selph sells stool and blood tests that you can take at home. The test results will be reviewed by a doctor and shown to you on your personal dashboard. Although the available tests include biomarkers found in typical тАЬgeneral healthтАЭ panels, their special focus is on gut health.
fields.bio: SelphтАЩs personalised health tools are powered by medical professionals and scientists. Experts in gut and metabolic health, weтАЩll get to the bottom of any troublesome symptoms, or pick up long-term health problems, with at-home test kits. Armed with accurate results, weтАЩll empower you to become the expert in your own health, providing a personal, evidence-based action plan to help you live better for longer.

fields.name: Alphabiolabs
fields.description: Alphabiolabs offers genetic testing. This includes  non-invasive prenatal testing, ancestral and relationship testing etc. They also have COVID testing, STI testing and trace metal testing.
fields.bio:
Established in 2004, and headquartered in Warrington, Cheshire, we are the UKтАЩs leading laboratory offering DNA, drug, alcohol, and health testing.

Our customer base spans the public, family & immigration solicitors, social services, businesses, academic institutions, and even the media.

We employ some of the foremost scientists in their fields of expertise, and have invested heavily in our UK laboratory, enabling us to test the widest variety of samples including cheek cell DNA, urine, oral fluid, hair, nails, blood and other biological samples.

We also operate a UK-wide network of walk-in centres and specially trained clinicians, making it easy to arrange a sample collection appointment at a time to suit you.

All legal and social work professionals can also benefit from FREE sample collections at any of our walk-in centres for legally-instructed DNA, drug and alcohol tests.

fields.name: Self Check
fields.description: Selfcheck sells at home lab test kits for a selection of common conditions. The choice of biomarkers is rather limited when compared to some competitors but their tests donтАЩt require lab-analysis, which makes them immediately interpretable. The test kits and methodology will be familiar to anyone who has used COVID antigen tests or urine pregnancy tests.
fields.bio:
SELFCHECK self-test kits are assembled at our UK facility according to a full medical device quality assurance system. All key components are manufactured either by UK or EU certified medical device companies.

The growing range of self-test kits can be found in many major UK retailers as well as independent pharmacies.

Our aim with SELFCHECK is to ensure that you can access high quality self-test kits that are based on the same clinically proven principles found in hospital laboratory tests used by your doctor, along with professional customer care.

Medical tests, whether used at home or in the hospital lab are regulated in the UK and EU in exactly the same way, ensuring that your tests are safe, easy to use to use and give reliable results. As such, all SELFCHECK medical tests are CE certified for self test use according to the In Vitro Diagnostics Directive/Regulations (IVDD/R) and registered with MHRA.

fields.name: Zoomdoc
fields.description: Zoomdoc is a telemedicine company that offers online GP consultations, medical letters and home blood testing kits for common biomarkers. You also get the results via email, accompanied by advice by GP.
fields.bio:
Our mission is to disrupt conventional healthcare models in the firm belief that nobody should have to wait to get well.
Online consultations and home health-testing services allow patients to take control of their health and well-being. We have also revolutionised тАШnon-NHSтАЩ medical letters тАУ removing the need for a GP appointment and relieving pressure on the NHS.

fields.name: EasyDNA
fields.description: EasyDNA offers genetic testing for clinical conditions, ancestry, paternity, relationships. They also offer wellness-oriented testing, such as for sports. They also provide detailed explanation of the test results.
fields.bio: EasyDNA UK specialises in providing DNA tests that are affordable, accurate and confidential. Our home paternity test is on special offer at just ┬г99 for a limited period. There are NO EXTRA FEES. Sample collection is performed using our easy-to-use DNA test kit. Your DNA paternity testing results are ready in only 3-5 working days. We also offer the option of getting results in 3 to 4 working days with our express service (from receipt of samples at the laboratory). EasyDNA tests 21 genetic markers for total accuracy so you can have the peace of mind that you need. A home paternity test provides a 99.99% accurate result if the alleged father is the biological father and a 100% accuracy if he is not.

fields.name: 23andMe
fields.description: 23andMe is one of the best established and well known genetic ancestry services on the market. They also offer health and wellness related analysis. Their service comes with extensive reports, either through their app or otherwise, for understanding your results. Note that their laboratories are located in the US and therefore fall under US legislation.
fields.bio:
23andMe is a leading consumer genetics and research company. Founded in 2006, our mission is to help people access, understand, and benefit from the human genome. We want to disrupt the healthcare experience by building a personalized health and wellness experience that caters uniquely to the individual by harnessing the power of their DNA. 23andMe pioneered direct access to genetic information as the only company with multiple FDA clearances for genetic health reports.

We have built the worldтАЩs largest crowdsourced platform for genetic research, with 80 percent of our customers electing to participate. This platform allows us to accelerate research at an unprecedented scale, while providing information back to participants. Our Therapeutics team leverages this research platform to identify and develop drug targets rooted in human genetics across a spectrum of disease areas, including oncology, respiratory, and cardiovascular diseases.

fields.name: DNA at Home
fields.description: DNA at Home sells relationship - oriented DNA tests. These include paternity, sibling, grandparent etc. They do not sell genetic testing for wellness or diagnosis.
fields.bio:
Established in 1987, Cellmark pioneered the introduction of DNA testing for paternity and relationship analysis at our DNA laboratories in Abingdon, Oxfordshire. We provide rapid, reliable, quality accredited paternity and relationship testing - with over 35 years' experience we provide a service you can trust.

We deliver a next day service as standard for all our customers, for paternity, maternity, sibling, uncle/aunt relationships, grandparent testing and immigration matters. If your samples reach us by 10am we aim to get the test report to you by the end of the next working day, at no extra cost!

You can order kits online or by calling us free on 0800 043 1987 - our friendly customer services team are experienced at dealing with confidential matters and are here to help.

fields.name: Myogenes
fields.description: Myogenes sells health-related DNA tests, such as for pharmacogenetics, hereditary cancer screening, mental health predispositions and general health and wellness predictions. The test results are delivered to your clinician and will be interpreted with them.
fields.bio:
At Myogenes we believe thereтАЩs no place for тАШtrial and errorтАЩ in modern medicine. ThatтАЩs why our experts have spent years formulating a series of tests which offer you real insights into your probability of developing certain critical illnesses.

WhatтАЩs more, should you ever require medication in the future, our tests will also highlight to your doctor any prescribed drugs that could cause you adverse, or even fatal side effects.

fields.name: 24Genetics
fields.description: 24Genetics provides a range of genetic testing services. They offer DNA tests for pharmacogenetics, ancestry, nutrition, sports, and personality. Additionally, they conduct oral microbiome testing.
fields.bio: With thousands of clients in more than 100 countries, 24Genetics is one of the most relevant companies in the sector. We perform all laboratory work and algorithmic processing in Europe. We do so under the strictest European regulations. 24Genetics is formed by an international team of proven scientific prestige, and our tests are recognised by the NCBI. The NCBI is the worldтАЩs leading genetics organisation. We ship our tests anywhere in the world. Moreover, they are available in several languages.

fields.name: Color
fields.description: Color offers DNA testing, mostly for predicting cancer and chronic disease risk but also pharmacogenomics analysis for common medications. Their reports are based on American Cancer Society guidelines. The results include a detailed geneticist report.

fields.name: AffinityDNA
fields.description: AffinityDNA UK offers a wide range of DNA Tests including Paternity, Relationship, Prenatal (NIPT), Ancestry, Health and Animal testing. Their health tests include food intolerance, gut microbiome, skin care DNA, disease risk assessment etc.
fields.bio: AffinityDNA is an industry-leading DNA Testing company with more than 15 yearsтАЩ experience in the DNA business and established partnerships with some of the most highly accredited DNA testing laboratories in the world. We provide the most accurate and reliable test results available and monitor our partner laboratories constantly to ensure your complete peace of mind.

fields.name: SelfDecode
fields.description: SelfDecode is a subscription-based service that offers you health and (more so) wellness-oriented insights based on genetic data. You can either upload existing genetic information or order a test from SelfDecode. When compared to most companies in this field, SelfDecode is more heavily geared towards wellness, fitness and biohacking.
fields.bio: SelfDecode is a personalized health report service, which enables users to obtain detailed information and reports based on their genome. SelfDecode strongly encourages those who use our service to consult and work with an experienced healthcare provider as our services are not to replace the relationship with a licensed doctor or regular medical screenings.

fields.name: myDNAHhealth
fields.description: MyDNA offers wellness, and more specifically, nutrition - oriented genetic testing. The report includes lifestyle, nutrition and exercise plans. They also sell supplements.
fields.bio:
WeтАЩve been bringing high-level, useful DNA reports to customers since 2014. Through using leading DNA testing results combined with a lifestyle analysis, our in-depth reports give you the vital information you need to make positive lifestyle changes that are perfectly adapted to you.

Did you know that 40% of preventable mortality is a result of diet and lifestyle choices, followed by 30% that can be attributed to genetics? As a result, our DNA testing services have been created with these two key factors in mind. The combined approach means you receive actionable results that can have a direct and positive impact on your wellbeing.

fields.name: DNAfit
fields.description: DNAfit is a genetics-based wellness and nutrition company. They offer genetic testing or analysis of existing genetic data to provide personalised fitness and nutrition plans.
fields.bio:
DNAfit supports you every step of the way on your genetic wellness journey.

Grounded in the evolving research from our Scientific Advisory Board, our products put you in charge of your health. Our convenient online platforms make eating and training to your genes as simple and hassle-free as possible.

Our team of fitness and nutrition professionals provide you with expert guidance along the way. WeтАЩre there to ensure you reach your goalтАУwhatever that may be.

fields.name: CircleDNA
fields.description: CircleDNA offers genetic testing for a wide range of markers, from wellness and lifestyle to disease risk prediction and pharmacogenomics. They also have an ancestry component available. The results are provided in their mobile app. Genetic counselling is available.
fields.bio:
Founded in 2014, Prenetics is a major global diagnostic and genetic testing company with the mission to bring health closer to millions of people globally and decentralize healthcare by making the three pillars тАФ Prevention, Diagnostics and Personalized Care тАФ comprehensive and accessible to anyone, at any time and anywhere.

On May 18th 2022, Prenetics made international headlines to become Hong KongтАЩs First Unicorn to publicly list on the Nasdaq with the ticker symbol тАЬPREтАЭ.

fields.name: LivingDNA

fields.bio: The separation between people & countries is at the highest its ever been. Our health systems are nearing bankruptcy yet 80% of illness and disease is preventable and lifestyle-related. What if we could change that? What if through the power of DNA and the way it's delivered we are able to re-connect with ourselves and each other. What if as a result, we start to live a more enriched and healthy life? We see that as more than possible.

fields.name: SiPhox
fields.description:
Siphox offers at home testing for 17 biomarkers. They also have a subscription-based service where members can either have unlimited tests sent to them (fee taken after each use) and a new kit sent immediately after the previous one has been used. Or they can opt for quarterly or yearly testing.

fields.name: Everlywell
